{
  "doc_id": "12644",
  "text": "Melanin is a biologically important pigment found throughout the animal kingdom. The two major, chemically distinct groups of melanins are the brown-to-black eumelanins and the yellow-to-reddish pheomelanins [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , and it is the quantity and quality of these pigments that determine the color of the hair, skin, and eyes of animals [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Various organisms employ these pigments in diverse and vital roles, such as camouflage, sexual attraction, and photoprotection [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] . Despite their significance, melanins remain poorly characterized due to their insolubility and their extreme molecular heterogeneity [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] [CITATION_15] [CITATION_16] . Furthermore, the regulatory mechanisms that control their biosynthesis remain poorly understood [CITATION_17] . To better understand the diverse constituency of melanins, it is important to study their composition and the regulation of their biosynthesis in model organisms.",
